Sam,<br>
I wish it were as simple as the &quot;old soldier's&quot; cry, but after WWII and the Nuremburg trials, that won't play any more.  In an ambiguous situation, I believe one goes with one's country, but ultimate moral assurance may not be found.  You do the best you can with your knowledge, principles and conscience.  And Vietnam was ambiguous for a variety of reasons.  The setting up of South Vietnam; because the US was afraid Ho Chi Minh would win a free election is one.  The US's tacit blessing to Diem's assasination is another.  And that's not saying some heads would not have rolled with the communists taking power.  But I'm betting the eventual war cost more.  Anybody with any sense should have known that a forced settlement wouldn't be accepted as permanent and binding by the North Vietnamese.<br><br>
To protect the defenseless from bullies is honorable, but it can't be done blindly.  There must be an honest, accurate appraisal of goals and whether one has the means to accomplish them.  Otherwise lives are needlessly lost.  Our entry into Vietnam does not meet this test.  Even assuming less mistakes leading to a military victory does not automatically guarantee a won peace, a stable peace.  No one has yet taken up my challenge made a few threads back on this.
